2026-03-28 | Construct String from LCP Matrix

•	You are given an n × n matrix `lcp`.  
•	lcp[i][j] = length of longest common prefix of suffixes:
		word[i…] and word[j…]  

•	Goal:
		reconstruct the **lexicographically smallest string** that satisfies this matrix.  

•	If impossible → return "".

	Key Observations
1.	If lcp[i][j] > 0:
		word[i] == word[j]  
2.	If lcp[i][j] = k:
		then for next k positions:
			word[i+x] == word[j+x]  
3.	If mismatch occurs → invalid matrix  

	Approach
1.	Use **Union-Find (DSU)**:
		group indices that must have same character  
2.	For every (i, j):
		if lcp[i][j] > 0:
			union(i, j)  

3.	Assign characters:
		for each group assign smallest unused character  
		(limit 26 letters → if exceed → impossible)

4.	Build string  

5.	Validate:
		recompute LCP matrix from constructed string  
		if mismatch → return ""

	Time Complexity
	O(n²)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:

    struct DSU {
        vector<int> parent;

        DSU(int n){
            parent.resize(n);
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++) parent[i]=i;
        }

        int find(int x){
            if(parent[x]!=x)
                parent[x]=find(parent[x]);
            return parent[x];
        }

        void unite(int a,int b){
            a=find(a), b=find(b);
            if(a!=b) parent[b]=a;
        }
    };

    string findTheString(vector<vector<int>>& lcp) {

        int n = lcp.size();
        DSU dsu(n);

        // Step 1: group equal indices
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(lcp[i][j] > 0)
                    dsu.unite(i,j);
            }
        }

        // Step 2: assign smallest characters
        unordered_map<int,char> mp;
        char ch = 'a';

        string res(n,'?');

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            int p = dsu.find(i);

            if(!mp.count(p)){
                if(ch > 'z') return "";
                mp[p] = ch++;
            }

            res[i] = mp[p];
        }

        // Step 3: validate LCP
        vector<vector<int>> calc(n, vector<int>(n,0));

        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--){
            for(int j=n-1;j>=0;j--){
                if(res[i]==res[j]){
                    calc[i][j] = 1;
                    if(i+1<n && j+1<n)
                        calc[i][j] += calc[i+1][j+1];
                }
            }
        }

        if(calc != lcp) return "";

        return res;
    }
};

	Key Insight
The LCP matrix enforces **equality constraints across indices**.  
Union-Find groups these constraints, and greedy assignment ensures lexicographically smallest string.  
Final validation guarantees correctness.
